{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531190"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:12:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:12:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14585"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14585"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.04,0.1,0.84,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7278"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57144"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7278"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42603"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"},{"type":"tags","id":"2943"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3186"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4838"},{"type":"tags","id":"5568"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17773"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57144"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with two days of confusion, diarrhoea and vomiting. His wife reports he was previously independent and living at home with her. Over the past 24 hours, he has become increasingly agitated and disorientated. He has a medical history of hypertension, atrial fibrillation, osteoarthritis, and benign prostatic hyperplasia. His regular medications are apixaban, amlodipine, paracetamol, and tamsulosin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell and agitated. His pulse rate is irregularly irregular at 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He is disorientated to time and place with a fluctuating level of consciousness. His mouth is dry with reduced skin turgor. His abdomen is soft and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 130 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EPotassium: 3.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EChloride: 90 mmol/L (95-105)\u003Cbr /\u003EBicarbonate: 15 mmol/L (22-32)\u003Cbr /\u003EUrea: 15.0 mmol/L (2.5-7.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine: 180 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003Cbr /\u003EMagnesium: 0.6 mmol/L (0.7-1.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count: 8.0 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stool culture","Haloperidol","Oral rehydration solution","Intravenous crystalloid fluids","Computed tomography brain scan"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with delirium in the context of severe dehydration from presumed viral gastroenteritis. The key features supporting delirium include acute onset confusion, fluctuating consciousness, and disorientation. His blood tests show pre-renal acute kidney injury with multiple electrolyte derangements including hyponatraemia, hypokalaemia, hypochloraemia, metabolic acidosis, and hypomagnesaemia, all consistent with significant fluid losses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous crystalloid fluids\u003C/strong\u003E are the most appropriate initial management. Rapid rehydration will help correct the underlying cause of delirium, improve renal function, and begin to correct the multiple electrolyte abnormalities. The patient\u0027s low blood pressure, tachycardia, and severe biochemical derangement indicate significant dehydration requiring immediate intervention. Targeted electrolyte replacement, particularly potassium and magnesium, should follow initial fluid resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral rehydration solution\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the patient\u0027s confused state, severity of dehydration, and multiple electrolyte derangements. There is a risk of aspiration, and the degree of physiological disturbance requires more rapid correction than can be achieved orally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered for severe agitation that poses immediate risk, but it should not be the first-line treatment. The priority is to treat the underlying cause of delirium rather than simply sedate the patient. Additionally, antipsychotics should be used with caution in the setting of electrolyte abnormalities which may increase the risk of QT prolongation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography brain scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated urgently if there were focal neurological signs or history of head trauma, which are not present here. While the patient is anticoagulated with apixaban, there is no history of falls or trauma, and the clinical picture is consistent with delirium secondary to severe dehydration and metabolic derangement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStool culture\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful for public health purposes or if bacterial infection is suspected, but it will not change the immediate management. The absence of fever and normal white cell count suggest a viral cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Delirium requires prompt identification and treatment of underlying precipitants, with rehydration being first-line for dehydration-induced delirium.","Common features of delirium include acute onset, fluctuating course, inattention, and disorganised thinking.","Elderly patients with gastroenteritis are at high risk of dehydration and subsequent delirium due to reduced physiological reserve."],"references":["Wan M, Chase JM. Delirium in older adults: Diagnosis, prevention, and treatment. Br Columbia Med J. 2017 Apr 1;59(3):165-70. Available online at ; https://bcmj.org/articles/delirium-older-adults-diagnosis-prevention-and-treatment","Mart MF, Roberson SW, Salas B, Pandharipande PP, Ely EW. Prevention and management of delirium in the intensive care unit. InSeminars in respiratory and critical care medicine 2021 Feb (Vol. 42, No. 01, pp. 112-126). Thieme Medical Publishers, Inc.. Available online at ; https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7855536/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42603"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14585"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42603"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-24T19:04:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T19:07:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7278"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57144"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"descr